components.label: Content

components.html:
This form is for the demonstration and review of the form segments and their generated flags.

Things that will not display on the final form:

  1. This intro.
  2. The "PDF Output Ready Version" button at the bottom before the submit button.

Instructions:

  1. To fill out the DMER as a Commercial DMER you will have to set it in Mercury
  2. Click the "PDF Output Ready Version" button to view the page the way the submitted PDF will be displayed and see the flags that will go to Mercury.
  3. The Submit button currently only transfers flag information to DEV Mercury. PDF Generation is in developement.
  4. Buttons requesting the user to complete another segment that is not present will be functional when the required segment has been added.  Until then these buttons are non functional.

A DEMO page is available for the evaluation of form segments and may have more segments available at this time.  The form segments here will be copied directly from the Pre-Integration form unchanged.

components.tooltip:
Epilepsy with medication change – Commercial drivers
This standard applies to commercial drivers with epilepsy who undergo a prescribed change to, or withdrawal of, an effective antiepileptic medication. This standard only applies where the driver’s treatment was effective (i.e. their epilepsy was controlled) prior to the change to, or withdrawal from, medication.  This means they must first meet guideline 17.6.12  
A 5-YEAR SEIZURE-FREE PERIOD PREVIOUSLY ESTABLISHED  before this standard will apply.

Epilepsy with medication change – Non-commercial drivers
This standard applies to non-commercial drivers with epilepsy who undergo a prescribed change to, or withdrawal of, an effective antiepileptic medication. This standard only applies where the driver’s treatment was effective (i.e. their epilepsy was controlled) prior to the change to, or withdrawal from, medication. This means they should not have had a seizure for at least six months prior to the change or withdrawal of medication.  If their treatment prior to the change was not effective, then guideline 17.6.6 applies.
